\begin_layout Standard
This example shows that the best linear approximation of a linear function
 at any point is the linear function itself and the rate of change is the
 factor 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 of the input variable, called 
\emph on

\begin_inset LatexCommand index
name "the slope"

\end_inset

the slope
\emph default
.
 The situation changes when we consider arbitrary functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 In that case the value of the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{f(x_{1})-f(x_{0})}{x_{1}-x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 will depend on the choices of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 But since we are interested in the best linear approximation of the function
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
at the point
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, we fix 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 just to be a infinitesimal step away from 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Mathematically this is expressed in terms of a limit.
 We do not go into the details of limits here, but merely demonstrate, how
 the derivative of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 is defined.
 The rate of change with a infinitesimal close point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=x_{0}+h$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
f'(x) & = & \lim_{h\rightarrow0}\frac{f(\overbrace{x_{0}+h}^{=x_{1}})-f(x_{0})}{\underbrace{h}_{=x_{1}-x_{0}}}.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The ''
\begin_inset Formula $\lim$
\end_inset

