 a linear function for 
\begin_inset Formula $b\not=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is just one last generalization left, that we have to take care of
 : If 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\not=0$
\end_inset

, then we cannot simply choose 
\begin_inset Formula $b=f(x_{0})$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
g(x_{0}) & = & wx_{0}+b\\
 & = & f'(x_{0})x_{0}+f(x_{0})\\
 & \not= & f(x_{o})\mbox{\mbox{for }}w,x_{0}\not=0.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

However, we can fix this by a simple trick: We just subtract 
\begin_inset Formula $wx_{0}=f'(x_{0})x_{0}$
\end_inset

 to enforce 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x_{0})=f(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 By this, we arrive at the general form of a linear approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

