\begin_layout Subsection
Finding Extreme Points of a Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Derivates can be used to find global minima or maxima of functions.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has a local maximum (resp.
 minimum) at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x_{0})=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f''(x_{0})<0$
\end_inset

 (resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f''(x_{0})>0$
\end_inset

).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x_{0})=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f''(x_{0})=0,$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 is said to be a saddle-point.
 
\end_layout

