\begin_layout Standard
So far, the scalar product may seem as no more than a useful notational
 shortcut.
 However, it has a lot of nice properties and is use to compute a lot of
 interesting properties of vectors.
 Therefore, it is very important to get a good intuition for it.
 In the following we develop a few.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first one only applies to vectors of length one.
 Nevertheless, it is very useful.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Lemma (Angle between two vectors) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 have length one, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $||\mathbf{x}||=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $||\mathbf{v}||=1$
\end_inset

, the scalar product is the cosine of the angle between the two vectors:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\langle\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v}\rangle & = & \cos\measuredangle\{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v}\}.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align right
\begin_inset Formula $\Diamond$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this lemma we can already read off the geometrical interpretation of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v}\rangle=0$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 have non-zero length 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, respectively, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v}\rangle=0$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently 
\begin_inset Formula $||\frac{1}{a}\mathbf{x}||=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $||\frac{1}{b}\mathbf{v}||=1$
\end_inset

.
 Now we can rewrite the scalar product a little bit:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\langle\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v}\rangle & = & \sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}v_{i}\\
 & = & ab\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{a}x_{i}\frac{1}{b}v_{i}\\
 & = & ab\langle\frac{1}{a}\mathbf{x},\frac{1}{b}\mathbf{v}\rangle\\
 & = & ab\cos\measuredangle\{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v}\}.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v}\rangle=0$
\end_inset

, the cosine 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\measuredangle\{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v}\}$
\end_inset

 must be zero, which means that the angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $90^{\circ}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v}\rangle=0$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 form an angle of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\emph on

\begin_inset LatexCommand index
name "orthogonal"

\end_inset

orthogonal.
\end_layout

