\begin_layout Section
Fourier Series
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Decomposing a function into sines and cosines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we are looking at a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

which is defined on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[=\pi,\pi].$
\end_inset

 We want to decompose it into components that correspond to different frequencie
s, i.e.
 sines and cosines.
 
\begin_inset Formula $sin(x)$
\end_inset

 is a function that has exactly one 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

oscillation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\pi,\pi],$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin(2x)$
\end_inset

 exactly 2, 
\begin_inset Formula $sin(nx)$
\end_inset

 has exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 cycles.
 It turns out that (almost) any function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on this interval can be approximated arbitrarily well by functions of the
 form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
f_{\infty}(x) & = & b_{o}+a_{1}\sin(x)+b_{1}\cos(x)\\
 & + & a_{2}\sin(2x)+b_{2}\cos(2x)\\
 & + & a_{3}\sin(3x)+b_{3}\cos(3x)\\
 & + & ...\\
 & + & a_{n}\sin(nx)+b_{n}\cos(nx)\\
 & + & ...\\
 & = & b_{o}+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}(b_{k}\cos(kx)+a_{k}\sin(kx)),\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
 by a weighted sum of (possibly infininitely many) sines and cosines at
 different frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $n.$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is not differentiable, or 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\pi)\neq f(-\pi),$
\end_inset

 then the approximation might not be perfect, but is often good enough for
 practical purposes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This way of approximating function is reminscient of the approximation of
 functions by their Taylor Series, i.e a weight sum of the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $1,$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x,$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x^{2},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x^{3},$
\end_inset

etc...
 However, whereas the Taylor Series provided a 
\emph on
local
\emph default
 approximation to the function at some point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{o},$
\end_inset

 the approximation by the Fourier Series is global, i.e it is a good approximatio
n for any point on 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\pi,\pi].$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}=a_{k}^{2}+b_{k}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is often referred to as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

power at frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{k}{2\pi}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finding the coefficients
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to use this approximation in practice, we have to determine the
 coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{o},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{2},\ldots$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $a_{2},\ldots$
\end_inset

 For the Taylor Series, they were find by computing derivatives, for the
 Fourier Series, they are found by different integrations over 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will need the following identities, which we will just state here, but
 not prove (see problem sheet for that).
 For any integers and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m\neq k$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m\neq0$
\end_inset

 it is true that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{\pi}^{\pi}\sin(kx) & dx= & 0\\
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\cos(kx) & dx= & 0\mbox{}\\
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\sin(kx)\sin(mx)dx & = & 0\\
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\sin(kx)\cos(mx)dx & = & 0\\
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\cos(kx)\cos(mx)dx & = & 0\\
\\\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\sin(mx)\sin(mx)dx & = & \pi\\
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\sin(mx)\cos(mx)dx & = & 0\\
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\cos(mx)\cos(mx)dx & = & \pi.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While these identies might look complicated in writing, at least some of
 them are intuitive.
 One period of a sine consists of a positive first half, and a second half
 which is an identical copy of the first, just flipped into the negative
 numbers.
 Therefore, the integral across one oscillation is 0.
 Hence, if we integrat 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin(kx)$
\end_inset

, which has exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 oscillations on 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\pi,\pi],$
\end_inset

 this integral is 0.
 A similary reasoning can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin(kx)\sin(mx)$
\end_inset

 still integrates to 
\begin_inset Formula $0,$
\end_inset

provided that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq m.$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k=m,$
\end_inset

 we are integrating 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin(kx)\sin(kx)=\sin(kx)^{2},$
\end_inset

 which is nonnegative for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,$
\end_inset

and therefore can not integrate to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.$
\end_inset

 Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos$
\end_inset

are really just shifted copies of each other, so anything that we derived
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin$
\end_inset

 will also hold for 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{o}$
\end_inset

 can be found by integrating 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x):$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x)dx & = & \int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\left(b_{o}+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}(b_{k}\cos(kx)+a_{k}\sin(kx))\right)dx\\
 & = & \int_{-\pi}^{\pi}b_{o}dx+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\left(b_{k}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\cos(kx)dx+a_{k}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\sin(kx)dx\right)\\
 & = & 2\pi b_{o}+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\left(0+0\right)=2\pi b_{o}\\
\implies b_{o} & = & \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x)dx.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Any coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{m}$
\end_inset

 can be found by integrating the product 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\cos(mx)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x)\cos(mx)dx & = & \int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\left(b_{o}+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}(b_{k}\cos(kx)+a_{k}\sin(kx))\right)\cos(mx)dx\\
 & = & \int_{-\pi}^{\pi}b_{o}\cos(mx)dx+\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}b_{m}\cos(mx)\cos(mx)dx+\sum_{k=1,k\neq m}^{\infty}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}b_{k}\cos(kx)\cos(mx)dx\\
 &  & +\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}a_{k}\sin(kx)\cos(mx)dx\\
 & = & 0+\pi b_{m}+0+0=\pi b_{m}\\
\implies b_{m} & = & \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x)\cos(mx)dx.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{m}$
\end_inset

 can be found by integrating 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\sin(mx):$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
a_{m}=\frac{1}{\pi}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x)\sin(mx)dx.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In theory, we have to calculate infinetely many integrals in order to obtain
 the complete Fourier Series.
 However, in practice, it is usually sufficient to just compute a couple
 of them, just like we usually only computed the first couple of terms in
 the Taylor Series.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far, we restricted out attention to functions which were defined on the
 interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\pi,\pi].$
\end_inset

This simplifies notation considerably, and the general case of intervals
 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 can easily be reduced to this special case by a change of variables from
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x'=2\pi\frac{x-a}{b-a}-\pi.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fourier series and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

change of basis
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the linear algebra part of this course, we learnt that a set of vectors
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},v_{2},\ldots,v_{n}$
\end_inset

 is said to be orthonormal if each of them has length 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(\|v_{k}\|=\sqrt{\langle v_{k},v_{k}\rangle}=1)$
\end_inset

, and they are mutually orthogonal (
\begin_inset Formula $\langle v_{k},v_{m}\rangle=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m\neq k$
\end_inset

).
 We also saw that it is particularly easy to change coordinates from the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

standard
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 basis to any orthogonal basis by computing scalar products.
 To express a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\alpha_{1}v_{1}+\alpha_{2}v_{2}+\ldots+\alpha_{n}v_{n},$
\end_inset

 the new coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1},\ldots,\alpha_{n}$
\end_inset

 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}=\langle w,v_{1}\rangle,$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}=\langle w,v_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, etc.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, lets think of functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\pi,\pi]$
\end_inset

 as vectors: Just as the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th value of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is given by its 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th entry 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{k}$
\end_inset

, we can think of the 
\begin_inset Formula $"x"$
\end_inset

-th value of a function as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x).$
\end_inset

 Of course, there are infinetely many choices of 
\begin_inset Formula $x,$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is really an infinitely long vector, but lets ignore this technical nuisance
 for the moment.
 For example, when we are working in matlab, we usually represent 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

just by its values on some grid 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{o},x_{1},\ldots,x_{n}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider the 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset

set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 consisting of the 
\begin_inset Formula $2n+1$
\end_inset

 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}},\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}\sin(x),\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}\cos(x),\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}\sin(2x),\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}\cos(2x),\ldots,$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}\sin(nx),\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}\cos(nx).$
\end_inset

 Also, let us define the scalar product between two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 by the integral of their product: 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle f,g\rangle=\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x)g(x)dx.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Well, we can show that the integral identities that we had above imply that
 the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is orthonormal!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Firstly, identities X1, X2, X3 imply that each vector in the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has length 
\begin_inset Formula $1.$
\end_inset

 E.g for 
\begin_inset Formula $v(x)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}\sin(kx):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\|v\|=\sqrt{\langle v,v\rangle}=\sqrt{\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\frac{1}{\pi}\sin(kx)\sin(mx)dx}=\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{\pi}}=1\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Secondly, identities 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset

X4, X5, X6 imply that the vectors are orthogonal.
 E.g.
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}\cos(mx)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\langle v,w\rangle=\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\frac{1}{\pi}\sin(kx)\sin(mx)dx=0.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thirdly, when we want to represent a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

as a weighted combination of the vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $S,$
\end_inset

i.e.
 by its Fourier Series, we have to calculate the coefficients by computing
 scalar products between 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

and each 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

vector
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in S.
 E.g.
 the coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $v(x)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}\sin(kx)$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\alpha_{k}=\langle f,v\rangle=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi}}\int f(x)\sin(kx)dx.\]

\end_inset

 (Note that the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{k}$
\end_inset

 differ from the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\pi}$
\end_inset

, as we normalized each sine and cosine such that it has 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

length
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 1.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, one can think of going from a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 to its Fourier Series 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2},a_{3}\ldots$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $b_{o},b_{1},b_{2}\ldots$
\end_inset

 as changing the basis from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

normal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 basis to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

frequency
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 basis given by the (normalized) sines and cosines at different frequencies!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While this relationship between Linear Algebra and Analysis might seem a
 bit surprising (and useless), it really helps to sharpen our intuition
 about why the frequency-decomposition of a function is a useful thing to
 look at.
 It also explains the formulae for calculating the coefficients, which seemed
 to magically appear out of nowhere in the previous section.
 Furthermore, a similar logic can not only be applied to bases consisting
 of sines and cosines, but to very different sets of functions, as long
 as they are orthonormal.
 For example, we can represent a function using 
\emph on
wavelet coefficients.

\emph default
 In this case, the basis functions are given by special sets of functions
 called 
\emph on
wavelets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, in stochastic Fourier Analysis, which deals with random functions,
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

frequency
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 basis is often equivalent to the PCA-basis.
 Therefore, one can think of stochastic Fourier Analysis as doing PCA not
 on random vectors, but on certain classes of random functions.
 The general relationship between PCA and Fourier Analysis is beyond the
 scope of the course, but a nice informal treatment can be found in XXX.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Getting rid of the cosines: Amplitudes and phases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can get rid of alll the cosines in the Fourier Series of a function if
 we do not represent it by a linear combination of sines and cosines, but
 rather by a weighted sum of 
\emph on
shifted
\emph default
 sines.
 In other words, we want to write 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(x)=b_{o}+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}A_{k}\sin(kx-\phi_{k}),\]

\end_inset

where each 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
amplitude
\emph default
 at frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $k,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\emph on
phase
\emph default
 at that frequency.
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{k}$
\end_inset

 is a real number in 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,2\pi],$
\end_inset

 and tells us by how much we have to shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin(kx)$
\end_inset

 along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis.
 Once we have found the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

 by performing the integrations outlined above, we can calculate the amplitudes
 and phases using the trigonometric identiy
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sin(u-v)=\sin(u)\cos(v)-\cos(u)\sin(v).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By applying this identity to 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\sin(kx-\phi_{k}),$
\end_inset

we get that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
A_{k}\sin(kx-\phi_{k})=A_{k}\sin(kx)\cos(\phi_{k})-A_{k}\cos(kx)\sin(\phi_{k}).\]

\end_inset

By comparing this to our previous formulation 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\sin(kx)+b_{k}\cos(kx)$
\end_inset

, we can see that the two representations are equal if and only if
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
A_{k}\cos(\phi_{k}) & = & a_{k}\\
-A_{k}\sin(\phi_{k}) & = & b_{k}.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dividing the second equation by the first yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{-A_{k}\sin(\phi_{k})}{A_{k}\cos(\phi_{k})} & = & \frac{a_{k}}{b_{k}}\\
\implies\tan(\phi_{k}) & = & -\frac{a_{k}}{b_{k}}.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Squaring each of the two eqations, and adding them leads to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
A_{k}^{2}\cos(\phi_{k})^{2}+A_{k}^{2}\sin(\phi_{k})^{2} & = & a_{k}^{2}+b_{k}^{2}\\
A_{k}^{2}\left(\cos(\phi_{k})^{2}+\sin(\phi_{k})^{2}\right) & = & a_{k}^{2}+b_{k}^{2}\\
A_{k} & = & \sqrt{a_{k}^{2}+b_{k}^{2}}.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words, the amplitude at frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the square-root of the power at frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{k}{2\pi},$
\end_inset

 and the phase is given by the inverse-tangent of the ratio of the coefficients
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fourier Series and Complex Numbers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fourier Analysis is usually taught using complex numbers rather than sines
 and cosines.
 While this has the disadvantage of requiring at least some familarity of
 complex numbers, it makes notation much simpler, and is also conceptually
 more elegant.
 Furthermore, you will have to understand the complex-number notation in
 order to understand most references about Fourier Series.
 Therefore, we will quickly sketch the derivation of Fourier Series with
 complex numbers.
 Furthermore, this will set the stage for the Fourier Transform in the next
 section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A complex number 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 consists of a real part and an imaginary part:
\begin_inset Formula \[
z=a+bi,\mbox{ where }i=\sqrt{-1}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Any complex number 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 can also be written in its 
\emph on
polar
\emph default
 form 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $z=Ae^{i\theta}$
\end_inset

, 
\emph default
where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the modulus of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the argument of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can convert from the cartesian form to the polar form by 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\tan^{-1}(\frac{b}{a}),$
\end_inset

 and from polar to cartesian by 
\begin_inset Formula $a=A\sin(\theta),$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $b=A\cos(\theta).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In other words, any complex number 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $z=Ae^{i\theta}=A(cos\theta+i\sin\theta).$
\end_inset

This will allow us to collapse the sines and cosines into complex numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Fourier Series approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 in complex number notation is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
f_{N}(x)=\sum_{k=-N}^{N}c_{k}e^{ikx}.\]

\end_inset

 To find each coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{m},$
\end_inset

 we need to make use of the integration identity
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}e^{ix(k-m)}dx=\begin{cases}
2\pi & \mbox{for }k=m\\
0 & \mbox{for }k\neq m.\end{cases}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We only need 
\emph on
one 
\emph default
such identity when we are using complex numbers, rather than several ones.
 Furthermore, this identity can quickly be derived by using the basic integratio
n rule 
\begin_inset Formula $\int e^{ax}dx=\frac{1}{a}e^{ax}.$
\end_inset

 Hence, each coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{m}$
\end_inset

 is found by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x)e^{-ixm}dx & = & \int_{-\pi}^{\pi}\left(\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}c_{k}e^{ikx}\right)e^{-ixm}\\
 & = & \sum_{k=-\infty,k\neq m}^{\infty}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}c_{k}e^{ix(k-m)}dx+\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}c_{m}e^{ix(m-m)}dx\\
 & = & 0+2\pi c_{m}\\
\implies c_{m} & = & \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x)e^{-ixm}dx.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should be noted that, while each coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{m}$
\end_inset

 could be an imaginary number, the Fourier approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{N}(x)$
\end_inset

 is actually a real-valued function, as the imaginary parts of its components
 magically cancel out.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Fourier Transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Up to now, we looked at functions on a fixed interval (for convenience,
\begin_inset Formula $[-\pi,\pi]$
\end_inset

), and their representation as a Fourier Series, i.e.
 as a linear combinations of sines and cosines, where the period of each
 sine is an integer multiple of the base frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2\pi},$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 the frequencies are 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2\pi},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{2\pi},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{3}{2\pi},$
\end_inset

 etc...
 If we want to look at multiple functions at the same times, this is a somewhat
 annoying restriction.
 For example, one can not find an interval on which both 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\sin(\sqrt{2}x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=\sin(x)$
\end_inset

 have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

simple
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Fourier Series.
 If we choose the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\pi,\pi]$
\end_inset

, then the Fourier Series of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

is quite complicated, and has non-zero coefficients at all frequencies,
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

is not an integer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way around this problem is to use the 
\emph on
Fourier Transform
\emph default
, rather than the
\emph on
 Fourier Series
\emph default
, to represent a function in the frequency domain.
 We get rid of the fixed interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[-T,T]$
\end_inset

 by letting 
\begin_inset Formula $T\rightarrow\infty,$
\end_inset

 and by that, the sum 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}c_{k}e^{ikx}$
\end_inset

 over discrete coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k}$
\end_inset

 turns into an integral over the 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph on
\bar default
\noun default
\color inherit
spectral densities 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\omega),$
\end_inset

 
\emph default
for any real-valued frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\mathbb{R}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(x)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}c(w)e^{ixw}dx,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c(w)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
Fourier Transform
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x),$
\end_inset

 which is often written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f}(w)$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

is the 
\emph on
Inverse Fourier Transform
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $c(w).$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $c(w)$
\end_inset

 are sometimes referred to as a 
\emph on
Fourier Transform Pair
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can calculate the Fourier Transform of any function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{f}(w)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)e^{-iwx}dx,\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
provided that this integral exists.
 The notations and conventions can be ambiguous and vary between different
 communities : The FT is also sometimes defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f}(w)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)e^{-i\omega x}dx$
\end_inset

 or by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f}(w)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)e^{-2\pi i\omega x}dx.$
\end_inset

 These different conventions dont, in principle, matter, but one has to
 be careful not to be confused or get results wich are off by, say, a factor
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, we can rarely use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

actual
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x),$
\end_inset

 but rather have to work with discrete approximations, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is only given by a finite set of functions values 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f_{2},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ldots,f_{n}$
\end_inset

 In this case, one should use the 
\emph on
Discrete Fourier Transform
\emph default
, which is defined to be the vector with 
\begin_inset Formula $m-th$
\end_inset

 entry 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{f}_{m}=\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}f_{k}e^{-\frac{2\pi i}{n}km}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes, one can read sentences like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Figure X shows the Fast Fourier Transform of data Y
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in papers.
 This is slight nonsense, as the Fast Fourier Transform is an 
\emph on
algorithm
\emph default
 for computing the DFT, and not something one could plot.
 Of course, they mean that the DFT of the data is shown.
\end_layout

